This paper discusses the architecture of a wireless communication system that uses random residue sequences for coding. This topic falls under the field of information theory (cs.IT) as it deals with the transmission and processing of information. Additionally, the use of random residue sequences provides cryptographic security, which falls under the category of computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the use of spread spectrum, which is a common technique used in wireless communication networks, making the paper relevant to the sub-category of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The system architecture described in the paper involves the use of coding and decoding algorithms, which falls under the sub-category of systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper may also be relevant to multimedia (cs.MM) as wireless communication systems are often used for transmitting multimedia content.
